{"type":"message","id":"45d6c5c4","parentId":"c12eb5db","timestamp":"2026-04-12T00:47:56.785Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is saying that OpenCode uses the same API as MiniMax. So OpenCode's API is actually compatible with MiniMax's API, or they're saying the OpenCode API key is the same as the MiniMax one. Let me check the OpenCode docs to see how it works with MiniMax.\n\nActually, looking back at the openclaw.json, there's already a minimax provider configured with `sk-cp-sPgdKbqLq4Ms_K5vTJUw6bJS3WjGmmbrvCQ8CNUyLyHZzACF_44tRK4oqcWNq5zCsjPANYk_oruPGv2m3_VGqjayHyZ07JSf8fUpbwcPhOx5vOAVNhUSZps` as the API key.\n \nWait, I'm re-reading what they said - \"en opencode usa el mismo api de minimax para conectarte\" - they're telling me to use the same MiniMax API for OpenCode. So OpenCode actually supports MiniMax as one of its backends, which means I can just point OpenCode at that existing MiniMax API key rather than setting up a separate one.\n\nLooking at the docs, OpenCode has its own catalog system with Zen and Go options, and it uses an API key for authentication. The user is essentially saying their MiniMax credentials should work directly with OpenCode. I need to figure out if there's a specific environment variable or configuration parameter that tells OpenCode to use MiniMax as the backend, since OpenCode typically expects its own API key but the user is saying this one should work.\n","thinkingSignature":"e48f2b6273b1f9873b4328643fe65e4096a8bc76ce33cbff8ca5ef0ced732851"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ish3b0rbdndm_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/providers/opencode-go.md 2>&1 | head -80"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":235,"output":386,"cacheRead":31424,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":32045,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775954871997,"responseId":"062a1eb873fbfabe91ab7970fbe8b67e"}}
{"type":"message","id":"c0f8afc2","parentId":"45d6c5c4","timestamp":"2026-04-12T00:47:56.824Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ish3b0rbdndm_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nsummary: \"Use the OpenCode Go catalog with the shared OpenCode setup\"\nread_when:\n  - You want the OpenCode Go catalog\n  - You need the runtime model refs for Go-hosted models\ntitle: \"OpenCode Go\"\n---\n\n# OpenCode Go\n\nOpenCode Go is the Go catalog within [OpenCode](/providers/opencode).\nIt uses the same `OPENCODE_API_KEY` as the Zen catalog, but keeps the runtime\nprovider id `opencode-go` so upstream per-model routing stays correct.\n\n## Supported models\n\n- `opencode-go/kimi-k2.5`\n- `opencode-go/glm-5`\n- `opencode-go/minimax-m2.5`\n\n## CLI setup\n\n```bash\nopenclaw onboard --auth-choice opencode-go\n# or non-interactive\nopenclaw onboard --opencode-go-api-key \"$OPENCODE_API_KEY\"\n```\n\n## Config snippet\n\n```json5\n{\n  env: { OPENCODE_API_KEY: \"YOUR_API_KEY_HERE\" }, // pragma: allowlist secret\n  agents: { defaults: { model: { primary: \"opencode-go/kimi-k2.5\" } } },\n}\n```\n\n## Routing behavior\n\nOpenClaw handles per-model routing automatically when the model ref uses `opencode-go/...`.\n\n## Notes\n\n- Use [OpenCode](/providers/opencode) for the shared onboarding and catalog overview.\n- Runtime refs stay explicit: `opencode/...` for Zen, `opencode-go/...` for Go."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":26,"aggregated":"---\nsummary: \"Use the OpenCode Go catalog with the shared OpenCode setup\"\nread_when:\n  - You want the OpenCode Go catalog\n  - You need the runtime model refs for Go-hosted models\ntitle: \"OpenCode Go\"\n---\n\n# OpenCode Go\n\nOpenCode Go is the Go catalog within [OpenCode](/providers/opencode).\nIt uses the same `OPENCODE_API_KEY` as the Zen catalog, but keeps the runtime\nprovider id `opencode-go` so upstream per-model routing stays correct.\n\n## Supported models\n\n- `opencode-go/kimi-k2.5`\n- `opencode-go/glm-5`\n- `opencode-go/minimax-m2.5`\n\n## CLI setup\n\n```bash\nopenclaw onboard --auth-choice opencode-go\n# or non-interactive\nopenclaw onboard --opencode-go-api-key \"$OPENCODE_API_KEY\"\n```\n\n## Config snippet\n\n```json5\n{\n  env: { OPENCODE_API_KEY: \"YOUR_API_KEY_HERE\" }, // pragma: allowlist secret\n  agents: { defaults: { model: { primary: \"opencode-go/kimi-k2.5\" } } },\n}\n```\n\n## Routing behavior\n\nOpenClaw handles per-model routing automatically when the model ref uses `opencode-go/...`.\n\n## Notes\n\n- Use [OpenCode](/providers/opencode) for the shared onboarding and catalog overview.\n- Runtime refs stay explicit: `opencode/...` for Zen, `opencode-go/...` for Go.","cwd":"/home/travis/Lookitry/Lookitry/sammy"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775954876820}}
{"type":"message","id":"8a069bd0","parentId":"c0f8afc2","timestamp":"2026-04-12T00:48:01.617Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is saying to use the same MiniMax API key for OpenCode. Looking at the config, the MiniMax API key is already set in openclaw.json:\n\n```json\n\"minimax\": {\n  \"baseUrl\": \"https://api.minimax.io/anthropic\",\n  \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n  \"apiKey\": \"sk-cp-sPgdKbqLq4Ms_K5vTJUw6bJS3WjGmmbrvCQ8CNUyLyHZzACF_44tRK4oqcWNq5zCsjPANYk_oruPGv2m3_VGqjayHyZ07JSf8fUpbwcPhOx5vOAVNhUSZps\",\n  \"models\": [...]\n}\n```\n\nBut wait - the docs say OpenCode uses its OWN API key, not MiniMax's. However, the user is insisting. Let me check if OpenCode supports MiniMax credentials...\n\nActually, looking at the docs more carefully:\n- `opencode-go/kimi-k2.5` - uses OpenCode API\n- `opencode-go/glm-5` - uses OpenCode API  \n\n\n- `opencode-go/minimax-m2.5` - uses OpenCode API\n\nThey're all OpenCode models. But the user says to use the same MiniMax API key... This might mean MiniMax hosts OpenCode's models or something. Or maybe the user is confused. Let me just follow what they say - configure OpenCode with the MiniMax API key and see what happens. I need to set up the opencode provider in openclaw.json using the same MiniMax API key that's already configured there.\n\nI'll add opencode-go/kimi-k2.5 as the model, enable the codex plugin for the harness, and set the default model accordingly. Let me check what's currently enabled in the config first.","thinkingSignature":"d18df214661cc79554483ecbe1d526f45b44d5646410e5e535cab84e0fe1c88a"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n¡Ah entendido! Usamos la API key de MiniMax que ya tienes configurada. Déjame actualizar la config para agregar **OpenCode Go** como provider con ese mismo key.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_pcn6tvmxc9lo_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/travis/.openclaw/openclaw.json"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minima